{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5361090-8aa1-4104-8063-c3659a08d94e","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file in the current directory.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it to speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or copy it in via `kubectl cp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a659eed-520a-4c2d-900c-1c7d21dc15aa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code task. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"A023:6C08C:8D0AAF:AC02CA:6A01303B"},"id":"481c0619-f23d-4afe-a3b9-02e075e6b65c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:26:30.092Z","parentId":"0f37c7ba-256f-4900-8cd8-cac5080a0e8f"}
